    "text": "Session 1 · RKS Design | RKS Marketing Onboarding ← Back to dashboard RKS Marketing Transition & Onboarding Dashboard / Session 1 · RKS Design RKS Design Human-centered innovation and product development Working Session 1 · RKS Design RKS Design: Marketing Overview & Ecosystem A complete reference for the RKS business, marketing ecosystem, positioning, audiences, people, approvals, systems, and pre-session exploration. Status Pre-session reference Brand RKS Design Session Working Session 1 On this page Company overview Positioning Audiences & proof Marketing ecosystem People & approval Files & platforms Before the session Session deliverables Company Overview This module is intended to preserve the full working context Helena needs before the live discussion. What RKS Design does Human-centered product development RKS combines research, strategy, industrial design, engineering, and development to create products, services, and experiences that people understand, adopt, and value. Company history More than four decades of practice RKS has built its approach through 45+ years of product-development work and the development of Psycho-Aesthetics® as a human-centered framework. Mission and philosophy Design for meaningful human response The company connects human needs and perception with business viability, technical feasibility, and long-term market value. Role of marketing Translate expertise into visibility and opportunity Marketing communicates RKS capabilities, demonstrates proof, supports credibility, and helps prospective clients understand when and why to engage the firm. Primary services Use the current RKS website service pages as the authoritative source for service language. The broader offering includes research, strategy, innovation, industrial design, engineering, development, and related product-development support. Industries served Use the current website and project portfolio to understand industry coverage. Healthcare and medical, consumer, technology, and commercial product-development work are especially visible in the portfolio. Positioning & Design Philosophy RKS is not simply an industrial design studio. It is an integrated innovation and product-development partner. Human-centered design is tied to business viability, engineering feasibility, adoption, and measurable outcomes. Psycho-Aesthetics® is an important foundation, but content should explain what it enables rather than relying on the name alone. RKS communications should be specific. Use projects, decisions, methods, and outcomes to make expertise tangible. Core Positioning Human-Centered Product Design & Innovation A human-centered product design and innovation firm that combines strategy, design, engineering, and Psycho-Aesthetics® to create products people love and businesses succeed with. Audiences & Proof Primary audiences Product, innovation, design, and business leaders People evaluating a product-development partner, solving an adoption problem, or deciding how to bring an opportunity to market. Audience work still needed Formal target-audience roadmap A more detailed audience framework should be added to the marketing roadmap during the transition. Notable-project source Portfolio and wins material Use the website portfolio and the internal wins PDF to identify the strongest project examples and measurable outcomes. Core evidence Case studies, visual essays, awards, outcomes Proof should come from specific project stories, client outcomes, recognized work, methodology, and long-term expertise. RKS Marketing Ecosystem Marketing functions as a connected system rather than a set of isolated channels. 01 Business priority Identify a service, project, audience, or opportunity that needs visibility. 02 Story and proof Define the message, evidence, audience, and intended action. 03 Asset creation Create website, SEO, visual essay, social, newsletter, video, or PR materials. 04 Review Route work through the correct internal and external reviewers. 05 Publish and extend Distribute, repurpose, optimize, and monitor. Core marketing pillars Website & SEO: technical SEO, blog SEO, keyword research, content publishing, and Google Search Console. Content marketing: blogs, visual essays, case studies, thought leadership, social assets, and reusable templates. Social media: project stories, expertise, company news, video, blogs, and native posts. Newsletter: monthly communication and process improvement. PR & earned media: press, awards, interviews, outreach, and coordinated website support. Video: interviews, project storytelling, studio capture, editing, and distribution. People, Ownership & Approval Ravi Messaging, positioning, strategy Leadership direction and final approval for major strategic communications. Lance Graphic design and visual portrayal Reviews visual essays, graphic design, and how RKS is represented visually. Ben Internal review and priorities Reviews work before leadership and helps align execution with current RKS needs. Alex Website, SEO, technical changes Supports SEO strategy, website updates, technical implementation, and search performance. Kathleen PR, press, and media Supports outreach, press materials, media coordination, and related communications. Helena Marketing execution and coordination Drafts, edits, publishes, organizes, coordinates reviews, and follows work through completion. Open the full marketing approval map → Files, Platforms & Working Systems The live session should clarify where active projects, templates, brand assets, calendars, SEO recommendations, credentials, and historical work are stored. SharePoint is the preferred internal file-sharing environment, but folder-level permissions should be checked before Helena relies on a link. RKS website: WordPress, Elementor, and WP Engine. SEO support: Alex’s recommendations and Google Search Console. Content and planning: Notion and shared internal folders. Design and production: Canva, Adobe tools, and approved brand assets. Video: studio equipment, DaVinci Resolve, Premiere, After Effects, Reduct, YouTube, and Vimeo as applicable. Open the platform directory → Before the Working Session Explore the RKS website and note how services, projects, people, and insights are organized. Review a mix of case studies, visual essays, blogs, press, and project pages. Identify language, claims, or navigation choices that feel clear, unclear, consistent, or inconsistent. Note where you would expect to find files, approvals, calendars, status, and historical context. Session Deliverables Complete the following after exploring both Session 1 modules and before the next working session. Questions Prepare 5–10 questions Document anything that is unclear about the brands, marketing ecosystem, responsibilities, approvals, platforms, resources, or processes. Observations Record 3 takeaways Capture three observations from your exploration, including anything that stood out, felt important, or helped clarify how marketing functions. Resource and process feedback Identify anything difficult to navigate Note any resources or processes you had difficulty locating or understanding, including missing documentation, unclear ownership, broken links, or areas where additional training would help. Bring these notes to Session 2 We will use your questions and feedback to clarify the marketing ecosystem and improve the onboarding materials. Return to Dashboard Also review PA-AI Session 1 →"
